06:19.820 --> 06:25.260
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:28.160 --> 06:29.660
And here are your hosts.

06:34.280 --> 06:35.400
This is Daryl Lane.

06:35.660 --> 06:36.380
And David Cruz.

06:36.880 --> 06:41.360
In 1973, Brian Aldis published a book on the origin and history of science fiction entitled

06:41.360 --> 06:42.440
Billion Years Spree.

06:42.900 --> 06:46.600
He gave us an interesting account of the reasons he wrote the book, including some comments

06:46.600 --> 06:48.700
on one of his novels, Barefoot in the Head.

06:49.560 --> 06:56.420
Well, I'd written a novel called Barefoot in the Head and it really didn't receive

06:57.400 --> 07:01.700
very kind initial attention, although the premise was simple enough.

07:03.040 --> 07:08.220
Barefoot in the Head was about the world stopped in its tracks by drugs.

07:08.520 --> 07:16.260
This was the late 60s, remember, when the Flower Power people had been around and we

07:16.260 --> 07:27.060
had had all this love in stuff and towards the end of the 60s the bills, as we say in

07:27.060 --> 07:32.640
England, the checks were coming in for all that kind of stuff and they were already finding

07:32.640 --> 07:38.960
the foetuses in the trash cans of Heat Ashbury so that Barefoot in the Head was an ambivalent

07:38.960 --> 07:40.740
book written in a difficult language.

07:41.180 --> 07:47.040
But I poured into it all I knew about A, science fiction and B, writing.

07:49.820 --> 07:58.340
I was a little surprised at the tepid response it got, the angry response it got, the anonymous

07:58.340 --> 07:58.800
letters.

07:59.060 --> 08:02.420
So I thought, well, let's me finish with the science fiction field.

08:03.780 --> 08:09.540
And I thought, well, before I leave it I ought to write down all that I know and love

08:09.540 --> 08:12.960
about it before I forget.

08:14.220 --> 08:19.300
And so really I settled down with that in mind to write Billionaire Spree and also to have

08:19.300 --> 08:24.820
an argument as I raised my hat and left the science fiction or community.

08:26.500 --> 08:34.300
But by the time I got to the end of the thing, you know, three years had passed and just

08:34.300 --> 08:37.120
writing the book turned me on to science fiction again.

08:38.060 --> 08:41.440
Billionaire Spree is full of Aldous's personal but fascinating ideas.

08:42.040 --> 08:46.920
One provocative idea, heresy to some science fiction fans, was that Hugo Gernsback, the

08:46.920 --> 08:50.140
father of modern science fiction, was a disastrous influence on the field.

08:50.520 --> 08:52.240
We asked Aldous what he meant by that.

08:52.940 --> 08:59.040
Well, as you probably know, that I did say something of that sort and since then people

08:59.040 --> 09:04.140
have been threatening to break my legs and my arms and shoot me and hang me and kick

09:04.140 --> 09:07.680
me out of the science fiction field and all sorts of things like that.

09:08.540 --> 09:21.100
But I guess that what I was worried about was the way science fiction was segregated

09:21.680 --> 09:34.120
by Gernsback into a magazine so that if you wanted to find science fiction you had to

09:34.120 --> 09:42.880
make a astounding or amazing or staggering which had a huge three-dimensional title with

09:42.880 --> 09:53.060
rivets in it and that resulted in a mono culture and we all know that there are dangers in

09:53.060 --> 09:54.080
mono culture.

09:55.240 --> 10:03.180
And I simply thought that the science fiction would be better as an uncaged animal that

10:03.180 --> 10:05.940
could rove at large where it would.

10:07.600 --> 10:15.160
But nowadays people complain that science fiction is segregated and that people think you're

10:15.160 --> 10:21.180
funny if you read it and that it has to have a special place in a bookshop right next to

10:21.180 --> 10:25.080
weirdo cult books about flying saucers or whatever.

10:25.920 --> 10:31.080
Well my answer to that is that yes, I agree, I think that's too bad.

10:31.080 --> 10:37.120
I think science fiction is much better than that but the reason why it is there is because

10:37.120 --> 10:40.980
of the segregation that was introduced by Hugo Gernsback.

10:41.700 --> 10:42.760
That was my argument.

10:43.940 --> 10:48.140
Anyone seeking to gain a perspective on science fiction and fantasy should read Billion Year's

10:48.140 --> 10:52.280
Spree, a personal but fascinating account of the field by one of science fiction's true

10:52.280 --> 10:52.840
men of letters.

