18:25.400 --> 18:26.700
This is Daryl Lane.

18:26.940 --> 18:27.660
And David Cruz.

18:28.160 --> 18:32.440
English science fiction author Brian Aldis sometimes writes books which are difficult to categorize.

18:32.440 --> 18:39.360
Aldis has written familiar science fiction such as his first novel, which was published in this country in 1959 as Starship.

18:39.860 --> 18:43.240
But many of his novels are experimental or avant-garde in both theme and structure.

18:43.640 --> 18:47.480
Report and Probability A published in 1969 is a good example of this type.

18:48.040 --> 18:55.100
A 1976 novel, though, The Melasia Tapestry, is one of his most unique novels, a strange but richly rewarding book.

18:55.400 --> 18:57.000
And it completely resists categories.

18:57.500 --> 18:59.900
It could be called science fiction, but it's not quite that.

18:59.900 --> 19:02.540
Some might say it's fantasy, but it's not that either.

19:02.820 --> 19:05.480
Aldis talks about the inspiration behind the book.

19:06.440 --> 19:12.120
The model I had was a pictorial one.

19:12.440 --> 19:13.320
That's often the case.

19:15.240 --> 19:22.080
Well, in several of my novels, I start from a pictorial beginning.

19:23.080 --> 19:37.040
And my pictorial beginnings with Melasia were the etchings which the Italian artist, the Baroque artist, G.B.T. Epileaux, made at the end of his life.

19:37.990 --> 19:52.880
Towards the end of his life, he retired and he started etching these mysterious little pictures of wizards,

19:52.880 --> 20:08.940
Monte Banks, soldiers, punchinellos, people being dug out of the ground from graves, owls, serpents burning on altars,

20:09.380 --> 20:12.820
all sorts of mysterious symbols in these lovely little pictures.

20:13.640 --> 20:15.880
And no one's actually figured out what they meant to be.

20:15.880 --> 20:25.160
It's like a science fictional alternative world where magic rules, I suppose you'd say,

20:26.040 --> 20:29.160
and I suppose that was one of the things I liked about them.

20:30.240 --> 20:38.700
So I thought, well, if no one else can reconstruct this world to their satisfaction, I'll have a go at it.

20:39.960 --> 20:48.700
And so I started writing short stories around the more haunting of these etchings of T.E.E.P.E.L.O.S.

20:49.680 --> 20:55.780
Melasia itself is a grand city which exists in what appears to be an alternate universe, suggestive of Earth's ancient past.

20:56.180 --> 20:59.840
There is no technology to speak of, sorcery of a limited sort seems to work,

21:00.160 --> 21:04.020
and there are all manner of exotic creatures such as flying beings which resemble humans.

21:04.020 --> 21:08.800
The novel's main concern is art, an unusual theme for a science fiction or fantasy book,

21:09.060 --> 21:11.060
seemingly more appropriate for a romantic poet.

21:11.500 --> 21:15.720
Aldous told us that the theme of art came out of a serious illness he had while writing the book.

21:16.740 --> 21:21.620
The effect of this internal complaint I had, this hepatitis,

21:25.400 --> 21:30.320
made me feel that, well, my lifespan was limited,

21:31.120 --> 21:37.900
and I'd frolicked about a good deal and had written some books that I perhaps didn't take as seriously as I should do,

21:39.280 --> 21:45.820
and that what I dearly loved was writing, and that I wanted to make a statement about art.

21:48.320 --> 21:53.020
And really, Melasia is, it's all about art from the title onwards.

21:53.020 --> 22:04.340
In other words, if the book has a power, it is the power of meditations on the nature of art,

22:04.600 --> 22:10.960
which is at once to transfigure, and at the same time to petrify.

22:10.960 --> 22:20.920
And as you know, Melasia itself is a city-state under a curse of zero change.

22:22.260 --> 22:26.500
Well, that's like a work of art, it's like Tia Pello's little etchings.

22:27.320 --> 22:32.740
They may be forever enigmatic to us, but they're forever unchanging.

22:33.560 --> 22:37.320
The Melasia Tapestry by one of the masters of modern science fiction,

22:37.320 --> 22:40.640
a difficult novel to categorize but a fascinating one to read.

