24:17.080 --> 24:18.380
This is David Cruz.

24:18.640 --> 24:19.240
And Daryl Lane.

24:19.700 --> 24:23.160
Brian Aldous' latest science fiction novel is the masterful achievement

24:23.160 --> 24:25.840
of an author who is at the height of his very awesome powers.

24:26.120 --> 24:29.480
It's called Heliconia Spring, and it's the first volume of a trilogy

24:29.480 --> 24:31.460
about an earth-like planet called Heliconia.

24:31.720 --> 24:34.140
Aldous tells us about the planet and the books.

24:35.640 --> 24:40.720
Heliconia is the name of a planet that's really much like Earth,

24:41.060 --> 24:43.900
and a lot of earth-like things go on there.

24:44.900 --> 24:51.040
But it is the child of binary suns,

24:51.080 --> 24:57.780
and it takes two and a half thousand years to go around the primary.

24:58.760 --> 25:02.160
I mean two and a half thousand Earth years.

25:04.840 --> 25:09.760
Which is to say that between one winter and the next,

25:10.820 --> 25:17.180
you can have a whole lot of civilizations doing a whole lot of declining and falling,

25:18.480 --> 25:21.380
and of course, falling and rising.

25:22.460 --> 25:32.520
And so that these three long volumes really just cover parts of one of Heliconia's great years.

25:33.520 --> 25:41.720
So there's at once this marvellous continuity, as I see it, of one year,

25:42.740 --> 25:45.900
and yet of many generations and many cultures.

25:47.920 --> 25:50.360
And that's the basic plan of the book.

25:50.840 --> 25:54.000
They're simply titled, The First One's Heliconia Spring.

25:54.200 --> 25:55.180
That's the one that's out.

25:55.640 --> 25:57.620
The one I'm writing is Heliconia Summer.

25:59.400 --> 26:02.380
And after that, I go on to Heliconia Winter.

26:03.820 --> 26:07.280
After centuries of a deadening winter, spring is coming to Heliconia,

26:07.660 --> 26:11.300
and the primitive men of the planet are waking up to the greater possibilities of life,

26:11.720 --> 26:15.600
to higher aspirations and knowledge, to the construction of a new civilization.

26:16.240 --> 26:20.660
The first volume traces the life of a nomadic hunter named Uli and his descendants.

26:21.540 --> 26:24.780
Because the first volume is about the sun bursting out.

26:25.940 --> 26:30.480
The first volume is just stacked full of things bursting out,

26:30.900 --> 26:34.260
and people bursting out, animals bursting out.

26:35.580 --> 26:37.680
It's a great bursting out novel.

26:45.560 --> 26:47.960
Circling Heliconia is a satellite from Earth,

26:48.360 --> 26:53.000
a huge observation station which monitors everything that happens in Heliconia and beams it to Earth.

26:53.000 --> 26:58.140
Aldous spent a painstaking four years on the book, striving for accuracy and realism.

26:59.300 --> 27:04.100
Well, I hope people will find that it's full of reality.

27:04.860 --> 27:08.680
That's why I say the moral of it should be mere existence,

27:09.100 --> 27:14.260
because I think they recognize their own lives passing through the book.

27:15.580 --> 27:22.900
And the other motive I had was that I grew rather alarm

27:22.900 --> 27:30.320
that the way so much science fiction, since it's become more popular,

27:31.400 --> 27:37.420
has been full of, what shall we say, fantasy, wish fulfillment.

27:38.480 --> 27:46.920
I didn't like that. I think that science fiction should reflect the facts of life,

27:48.120 --> 27:50.380
the hard facts of life.

27:51.020 --> 27:57.960
It shouldn't just be some nonsense about one guy against a malign empire

27:57.960 --> 28:02.600
who goes out and kills the chief baddie.

28:03.440 --> 28:06.520
I thought it should have a little more contact for reality.

28:07.300 --> 28:11.020
And moreover, I'll sound old fashioned if I say this,

28:11.020 --> 28:16.480
but I think that sort of thing is better for the nation's youth

28:17.020 --> 28:23.140
than the old hogwash about telepathic dragons and all the rest of it.

28:29.580 --> 28:32.140
Heliconia Spring is a remarkable and unique achievement

28:32.140 --> 28:34.540
by a man who is not just a great science fiction writer,

28:34.820 --> 28:36.600
but one of the finest writers of our time.

